\begin_layout Standard
The propagation of intense light through optical fibers is governed by the interplay between linear dispersion and the nonlinear response of the dielectric medium. In silica, the centrosymmetric lattice eliminates second-order nonlinearity, so the leading nonlinear effect is the Kerr term 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{(3)}$
\end_inset

. Starting from Maxwell's equations in a source-free, non-magnetic dielectric, the electric field can be written as a slowly varying envelope modulating a carrier: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbf{E}(\mathbf{r},t)=\tfrac{1}{2}\hat{\mathbf{x}}\bigl[F(x,y)\,A(z,t)\,e^{i(\beta_0 z-\omega_0 t)}+\text{c.c.}\bigr].
\]
\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x,y)$
\end_inset

 is the transverse modal shape set by the fiber's refractive-index profile, 
\begin_inset Formula $A(z,t)$
\end_inset

 is the envelope, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_0$
\end_inset

 is the propagation constant at the carrier frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_0$
\end_inset

. Applying the slowly varying envelope approximation and expanding the propagation constant to second order in frequency yields the nonlinear Schrödinger equation (NLS): 
\begin_inset Formula \[
i\partial_z A - \tfrac{\beta_2}{2}\partial_T^2 A + \gamma|A|^2 A = 0,
\]
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_2$
\end_inset

 is the group-velocity-dispersion parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=n_2\omega_0/(cA_{\text{eff}})$
\end_inset

 encodes the Kerr nonlinearity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In real fibers the refractive index is not spatially uniform. Fiber Bragg gratings impose periodic modulations, graded-index fibers create a parabolic transverse profile (an effective harmonic-oscillator potential), and photonic-crystal fibers achieve confinement via a micro-structured air-hole lattice. In every case, the spatial variation of the index enters the governing equations as an external potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

. The transverse modal equation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\nabla_\perp^2 F + \Bigl[\bigl(\tfrac{n\omega}{c}\bigr)^2(\mathbf{x}_\perp) - \beta^2\Bigr]F = 0
\]
\end_inset

is mathematically identical to the stationary Schrödinger equation 
\begin_inset Formula $-\Delta\psi + V(x)\psi = E\psi$
\end_inset

. Guided modes of the fiber correspond to bound states of this effective potential, and the fundamental mode is its ground state. This equivalence motivates the present work: engineering 
\begin_inset Formula $V(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 via refractive-index design directly translates into questions about the existence, uniqueness, and stability of ground-state solutions of the NLS with an external potential.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently, we study the stationary NLS 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}\label{eq:NLS}
(-\Delta + V + E)\psi + \sigma|\psi|^{2p}\psi = 0,
\end{equation}
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $V:\R^n\to\R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:\R^n\to\C$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $E\geq 0$
\end_inset

. The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 represents the energy (or, in the optical setting, the propagation constant). For each admissible 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 we seek ground-state solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_E$
\end_inset

 and analyze how their spatial structure is governed by the geometry of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

