(b)
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y_1=(0,h)^\intercal$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_2=(-a,-h/2)^\intercal$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_3=(a,-h/2)^\intercal$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $2a>1$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $|y_2-y_3|=2a>1$
\end_inset

 and the nearest-neighbor pairs are 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,2)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,3)$
\end_inset

 only) and the geometric constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $a^2+(3h/2)^2=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
From the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $y_1$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\HV y_1 &= \alpha_{12}(y_2-y_1)+\alpha_{13}(y_3-y_1) \\
(0,\lambda_2 h)^\intercal &= \bigl(a(\alpha_{13}-\alpha_{12}),\;-\tfrac{3h}{2}(\alpha_{13}+\alpha_{12})\bigr)^\intercal,
\end{align*}
\end_inset

which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{12}=\alpha_{13}=-\lambda_2/3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
From the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $y_2$
\end_inset

 (with only 
\begin_inset Formula $y_1$
\end_inset

 as nearest neighbor): 
\begin_inset Formula $\HV y_2 = \alpha_{12}(y_1-y_2)$
\end_inset

, yielding component-wise 
\begin_inset Formula $-a\lambda_1=a\alpha_{12}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-(h/2)\lambda_2=(3h/2)\alpha_{12}$
\end_inset

. The first gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{12}=-\lambda_1$
\end_inset

 and the second 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{12}=-\lambda_2/3$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_2=3\lambda_1$
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

